y. The\nstructure is also consistent with being due to two resonances. In addition, the\nnarrow excited $\\varXi^-$ states, $\\varXi(1690)^-$ and $\\varXi(1820)^-$, are\nseen for the first time in a $\\varXi_b^-$ decay, and their masses and widths\nare measured with improved precision. The analysis is performed using $pp$\ncollision data corresponding to a total integrated luminosity of 9fb$^{-1}$,\ncollected with the LHCb experiment at centre-of-mass energies of $7$, $8$ and\n$13$TeV.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 18 Dec 2020 17:50:26 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sun, 4 Jul 2021 13:09:56 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-07-06"}
{"id":"2012.10381","submitter":"Rair Macedo","authors":"Rair Mac\\^edo, Arjun S. Kudinoor, Karen L. Livesey, Robert E. Camley","title":"Breaking Space Inversion-Symmetry to Obtain Asymmetric Spin-Wave\n  Excitation in Systems with Nonuniform Magnetic Exchange","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Adv. Electron. Mater. 2021, 2100435","doi":"10.1002/aelm.202100435","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.mtrl-sci cond-mat.mes-hall physics.app-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We report on the consequences of non-uniform exchange in magnetic systems.\nThe quantum mechanical exchange interaction between spins is responsible for\nthe phenomenon of magnetic order, and is generally considered to be uniform\nacross bulk magnetic systems. Partly inspired by the Dzyaloshinskii-Moriya\ninteraction--also known as antisymmetric exchange--we use a linearly varying\nexchange interaction along a magnetic strip as a route to spatial inversion\nsymmetry-breaking. We find that, in addition to asymmetric modes and\nlocalization, spatially-varying exchange can be used to design nonreciprocal\nmagnetic signal excitation at frequencies that are tunable. Moreover, our work\npredicts nonreciprocity to occur across a vast range of frequencies up to\nhundreds of GHz. Such spin wave engineering is a key area of ongoing research\nin the fields of magnonics and spintronics, which are expected to enable the\nnext generation of communication technology. Analogous nonreciprocity is\nexpected to occur in other wave systems with gradient properties.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 18 Dec 2020 17:51:47 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 26 Apr 2021 16:29:58 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-09-22"}
