{"id":"2012.12194","submitter":"Maarten Biesheuvel","authors":"P.M. Biesheuvel","title":"The activity coefficient of $z$:1 ionic solutions scales with the cube\n  root of salt concentration","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.chem-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The activity coefficient of ionic solutions was proposed by Bjerrum (1916)\nand Ghosh (1918) to depend on the cube root of concentration, because of a good\nfit with data for low and moderate salt concentration. However, the\nDebye-H\\\"uckel (DH) theory that was developed later prevailed, and this theory\nhas a square root dependence. The derivation of the DH equation is not easy or\nintuitive, and has various uncertain elements, and the fit to data is not very\ngood for salts with non-unity valencies. We develop a model for the activity\ncoefficient based on the Coulomb force between an ion and its nearest-neighbour\nions of opposite charge, including the distribution of separations between the\nions. For a symmetric salt, we only have to analyze the interactions between\none cation and one anion, and we can derive an expression in the dilute limit\nthat depends on the Bjerrum length and the cube root of salt concentration,\nsimilar to a result already put forward by Bjerrum. For higher salt\nconcentrations or a non-zero size, numerical evaluation is required. For a 1:1\nsalt, this cube root dependence describes data of the activity coefficient very\nwell, both at low and intermediate salt concentrations, with also the prefactor\ncorrectly predicted. We also analyze an asymmetric 2:1 salt and 3:1 salt which\nrequires numerical solution of all possible orbits of two or three monovalent\nions around a central multivalent ion of opposite charge, and this calculation\nalso leads to a very good prediction of the activity coefficient that linearly\ndepends on the cube root of salt concentration up to moderate concentrations.\nFor 2:2 and 3:3 salts, numerical theory again fits data very well, but the cube\nroot limiting law does not apply. The theory can be extended to include ion\nvolume effects, for instance via the Carnahan-Starling equation of state.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 18 Dec 2020 17:57:14 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 6 Jan 2021 15:08:30 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Mon, 18 Jan 2021 18:53:04 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Mon, 16 Jan 2023 10:40:04 GMT"},{"version":"v5","created":"Sat, 4 Feb 2023 12:24:33 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-02-07"}
